msgid "Window Headers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/getting_started/basics/interface/window_system/headers.rst:6
# 57211bf4e21c48fda29a9ac4f2acb4a2
msgid "All windows have a header (the strip with a lighter gray background containing icon buttons). We will also refer to the header as the window *ToolBar*. The header may be at the top (as with the *Properties Window*) or the bottom (as with the *3D Window*) of a window's area. The picture below shows the header of the 3D window:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/getting_started/basics/interface/window_system/headers.rst:14
# 5880b6ab9e0143afbbd13a9fb5146cbd
msgid "If you move the mouse over a window, its header changes to a slightly lighter shade of gray. This means that it is \"focused\". All hotkeys you press will now affect the contents of this window."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/getting_started/basics/interface/window_system/headers.rst:20
# ff7419dd0acf4ac083a512ad7a9ece11
msgid "Hiding a header"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/getting_started/basics/interface/window_system/headers.rst:24
# 8069bb787e72437d99a9baae9df64a3d
msgid "To hide a header, move your mouse over the thin line between a window and its header, until the pointer takes the form of an up/down arrow. Then click, hold and drag with :kbd:`LMB` from the window over the header to hide the latter."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/getting_started/basics/interface/window_system/headers.rst:30
# c89ac3083fda4a218a9bd3f826e22236
msgid "Showing a header"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/getting_started/basics/interface/window_system/headers.rst:34
# 8e58f84de0c24d8994805946c200c42d
msgid "A hidden header leaves a little plus sign (see picture). By :kbd:`LMB` this, the header will reappear."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/getting_started/basics/interface/window_system/headers.rst:37
# 4a0b6da7d8d446c4865b79a514cda35c
msgid "Note 1: In the 3D window, there are up to two more of these little plus signs (to the top left and right of the window). Those will open panels with several tools, not a second header."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/getting_started/basics/interface/window_system/headers.rst:44
# 8e6e0b2844554993841f89f8c1a0b8c2
msgid "Note 2: In some windows, the mentioned plus sign can be hard to find, because it might look like a part of other icons. One example is the Outliner, in which there are other such plus signs, thus giving the one to get the header back good camouflage."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/getting_started/basics/interface/window_system/headers.rst:51
# 35abcd1942be4d5dada6ac9bfedefe6c
msgid "Header position"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/getting_started/basics/interface/window_system/headers.rst:53
# 2827c3078c604b0492ad95bad773a4a5
msgid "To move a header from top to bottom or the other way round, simply :kbd:`RMB` on it and select the appropriate item from the popup menu. If the header is at the top, the item text will read \"Flip to Bottom\", and if the header is at the bottom the item text will read \"Flip to Top\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/getting_started/basics/interface/window_system/headers.rst:59
# 5413629ec8f742a9b9ce4912e24a6ad9
msgid "Theme colors"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/getting_started/basics/interface/window_system/headers.rst:61
# fa12ece7a3f24d069fd4c28087cb5649
msgid "Blender allows for most of its interface color settings to be changed to suit the needs of the user. If you find that the colors you see on screen do not match those mentioned in the Manual then it could be that your default theme has been altered. Creating a new theme or selecting/altering a pre-existing one can be done by selecting the :doc:`User Preferences </preferences/index>` window and clicking on the *Themes* tab of the window."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/getting_started/basics/interface/window_system/headers.rst:69
# 7ca75a618a564d1cb3e3e6d99a72848b
msgid "Window type button"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/getting_started/basics/interface/window_system/headers.rst:71
# cf5814a1d53d4094b02beabcd491cea8
msgid ":kbd:`LMB` clicking on the first icon at the left end of a header allows selection of one of the 16 different window types. Every window frame in Blender may contain any type of window. So if you want 3D views everywhere, just go ahead and change them all."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/getting_started/basics/interface/window_system/headers.rst:78
# 1f2fde1c1ba74874988e5b47d9f2bb27
msgid "Menus and buttons"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/getting_started/basics/interface/window_system/headers.rst:80
# 131aba3a7c694cf989eb5746b40502d3
msgid "Most Window Headers, located immediately next to this first \"Window Type\" Menu button, exhibit a set of menus which can be hidden - again with a little minus sign. So if you cannot find a menu that was mentioned somewhere, try looking for a little plus sign (once again) next to the \"Window Type\" button. By clicking :kbd:`LMB` on it, the menu will come back."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/getting_started/basics/interface/window_system/headers.rst:86
# dd00767af2cc4a7f9da8fdf9cf110c0e
msgid "Menus allow you to directly access many features and commands, so just look through them to see what's there. All Menu entries show the relevant shortcut keys, if any."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/getting_started/basics/interface/window_system/headers.rst:90
# d8f210676b9e4dccb3f945e9d060f891
msgid "Menus and buttons will change with *Window Type* and the selected object and mode. They only show the actions that can be performed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/getting_started/basics/interface/window_system/headers.rst:95
# 1f82d4a637a14d1ea53f05fbb7895466
msgid "Collapsing Menus"
msgstr ""

